==English==

===Noun===
'''fun''' ([[uncountable]])
#A [[source]] of [[amusement]], [[enjoyment]] or [[pleasure]]
#[[Enjoyment]] or [[amusement]]
#[[Playful]] [[activity]], often [[noisy]]

====Translations====
*Dutch: [[plezier]] ''n'', [[lol]] ''m''
*German: [[Spaß]] ''m''
*Hebrew: [[כף]] ''m''
*Spanish: [[diversión]] ''f''

===Adjective===
'''fun''' (more fun, most fun)
#(''informal'') [[enjoyable]] or [[amusing]]

====Usage notes====
*Objections to the intensifiers ''funner'' and ''funnest'' stem from an archaic objection to the use of ''fun'' as an adjective. ''[[Funny]]'', the original adjectival form, has come to mean ''[[humorous]]'', leaving a void. Enter ''fun'' as an adjective. Grammarians once correctly battled this usage, but they lost, and ''fun'' is now a punchy alternative to ''[[enjoyable]]''. But the intensive forms of ''fun'' were thwarted, leaving us with the awkward, less-than-fun ''[[more fun]]'' and ''[[most fun]]'', which are so jarring to the ear that, despite their acceptance as standard usage, they almost never get used at all.

